In the present work, TLO can be significantly elevated because (i) the electron density is relatively high, (ii) the LO phonons do not spatially diffuse due to nearly vanishing group velocity, and (iii) the emitted LO phonons are of small wave numbers being confined within a narrow q-space sphere around the Brillouin zone centre, containing only a limited number of states (NOS = 4.00 × 1018/cm3)35 (see Supplementary Fig. 5 and Supplementary Note 4). If the electrical input power, p = Ej, is dissipated utterly via the emission of LO phonons, the rate of LO-phonon emission is given by ∂NLO/∂t = p/ ℏ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
